Final Demo: Monster Alignment Prediction

Goal: Predict monster alignment from biological + stat traits and lore text.

This notebook demonstrates the end-to-end workflow:

  • Load cleaned dataset
  • Show head and summary stats
  • Display EDA figures inline
  • Train and evaluate a baseline model (TF-IDF + Logistic Regression)
  • Report accuracy, precision, recall, F1, and show a confusion matrix
  • Test predictions on sample monsters
  • Summarize insights and conclusions

# 5) Prepare target labels (alignment) and features (TF-IDF over simple text fields)

def clean_alignment(text):
    if pd.isna(text):
        return "unknown"
    parts = str(text).split(",")
    if len(parts) > 1:
        return parts[-1].strip().lower()
    return str(text).strip().lower()

# Use same columns as baseline script
work_df = df.copy()
work_df["alignment"] = work_df["alignment"].apply(clean_alignment)
work_df["text_features"] = (
    work_df["name"].astype(str) + " " +
    work_df["size"].astype(str) + " " +
    work_df["armor_class"].astype(str)
)

X = work_df["text_features"].copy()
y = work_df["alignment"].copy()

# Drop tiny classes to avoid stratification issues
alignment_counts = y.value_counts()
valid_alignments = alignment_counts[alignment_counts >= 2].index
mask = y.isin(valid_alignments)
X = X[mask]
y = y[mask]

print("Classes (>=2 samples):", sorted(valid_alignments))
print("Samples:", X.shape[0])

Classes (>=2 samples): ['any alignment', 'any non-good alignment', 'any non-lawful alignment', 'chaotic evil', 'chaotic good', 'chaotic neutral', 'lawful evil', 'lawful good', 'lawful neutral', 'neutral', 'neutral evil', 'neutral good', 'unaligned']
Samples: 320
In[6]:
# 6) Train/test split, vectorize, train model
le = LabelEncoder()
y_encoded = le.fit_transform(y)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y_encoded, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y_encoded
)

vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=5000, stop_words="english")
X_train_vec = vectorizer.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_vec = vectorizer.transform(X_test)

model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=200, class_weight="balanced")
model.fit(X_train_vec, y_train)

y_pred = model.predict(X_test_vec)

acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
precision, recall, f1, _ = precision_recall_fscore_support(y_test, y_pred, average="weighted", zero_division=0)

print(f"Accuracy: {acc:.4f}")
print(f"Precision (weighted): {precision:.4f}")
print(f"Recall (weighted): {recall:.4f}")
print(f"F1 (weighted): {f1:.4f}")

print("\nClassification Report:\n")
labels_in_test = np.unique(y_test)
target_names = le.inverse_transform(labels_in_test)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, labels=labels_in_test, target_names=target_names, zero_division=0))

Insights & Conclusion

  • Models trained on basic biological/stat features and light text (name/size/AC) achieve moderate accuracy; performance varies by class frequency.
  • Class imbalance and ambiguous/compound alignment labels hurt precision/recall for rarer categories.
  • EDA shows strong prevalence of "unaligned" and clear differences in AC/HP distributions across sizes/CR.
  • Next steps to improve:
    • Incorporate full lore/description text into TF-IDF features.
    • Normalize compound labels (e.g., map "humanoid (any race)" cases) and rebalance classes.
    • Hyperparameter tuning and feature expansion (CR numeric, stats, types).
    • Try non-linear models or calibrated probabilities for better macro-F1.

# 6b) Enhanced labels + features (tabular + text)
import re
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC

# Simplify alignment labels and merge rare classes
def simplify_alignment(text: str):
    if pd.isna(text):
        return "unaligned"
    t = str(text).lower()
    if "chaotic evil" in t: return "chaotic evil"
    if "lawful evil" in t: return "lawful evil"
    if "neutral evil" in t: return "neutral evil"
    if "lawful good" in t: return "lawful good"
    if "chaotic good" in t: return "chaotic good"
    if "neutral good" in t: return "neutral good"
    if "unaligned" in t: return "unaligned"
    if "neutral" in t: return "neutral"
    return t.strip()

work2 = df.copy()
work2["alignment_simple"] = work2["alignment"].apply(simplify_alignment)

# Parse numeric challenge rating

def parse_cr(cr):
    if pd.isna(cr):
        return np.nan
    cr = str(cr).split()[0]
    if "/" in cr:
        num, denom = cr.split("/")
        try:
            return float(num) / float(denom)
        except:
            return np.nan
    try:
        return float(cr)
    except:
        return np.nan

work2["challenge_rating_num"] = work2["challenge_rating"].apply(parse_cr)

# Coerce numeric columns
for col in ["hit_points", "armor_class"]:
    work2[col] = pd.to_numeric(work2[col], errors="coerce")

# Merge rare labels to 'other' (threshold=5)
min_class_size = 5
counts = work2["alignment_simple"].value_counts()
rare = counts[counts < min_class_size].index
work2["alignment_simple"] = work2["alignment_simple"].replace(rare, "other")

features = ["name", "size", "hit_points", "armor_class", "challenge_rating_num"]
X2 = work2[features]
y2 = work2["alignment_simple"]

X2_train, X2_test, y2_train, y2_test = train_test_split(
    X2, y2, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y2
)

# Column-wise transforms: TF-IDF on name, OneHot on size, scale imputed numerics
text_features = ["name"]
cat_features = ["size"]
num_features = ["hit_points", "armor_class", "challenge_rating_num"]

preprocess = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ("text", TfidfVectorizer(max_features=2000, ngram_range=(1,2), stop_words="english"), "name"),
        ("cat", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore"), cat_features),
        ("num", Pipeline(steps=[
            ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="median")),
            ("scaler", StandardScaler())
        ]), num_features),
    ]
)

# Try a few strong baselines
models = {
    "LogReg": LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, class_weight="balanced"),
    "LinearSVC": LinearSVC(class_weight="balanced"),
}

best_name, best_acc, best_clf = None, -1.0, None
for name, clf in models.items():
    pipe = Pipeline(steps=[("prep", preprocess), ("clf", clf)])
    pipe.fit(X2_train, y2_train)
    acc = pipe.score(X2_test, y2_test)
    print(f"{name} accuracy: {acc:.4f}")
    if acc > best_acc:
        best_name, best_acc, best_clf = name, acc, pipe

print(f"\nBest model: {best_name} with accuracy {best_acc:.4f}")

LogReg accuracy: 0.4000
LinearSVC accuracy: 0.5846

Best model: LinearSVC with accuracy 0.5846

# 6d) Quick hyperparameter search (LogReg C)
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

logreg_pipe = Pipeline(steps=[("prep", preprocess), ("clf", LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, class_weight="balanced"))])
param_grid = {"clf__C": [0.2, 0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 5.0]}

gs = GridSearchCV(logreg_pipe, param_grid, cv=3, n_jobs=-1, scoring="accuracy")
gs.fit(X2_train, y2_train)
print("Best C:", gs.best_params_)
print("CV best acc:", f"{gs.best_score_:.4f}")

gs_acc = gs.score(X2_test, y2_test)
print("Test accuracy (LogReg tuned):", f"{gs_acc:.4f}")

Best C: {'clf__C': 5.0}
CV best acc: 0.5677
Test accuracy (LogReg tuned): 0.5846
